-- 
Indonesia Stock Movers: Bumi Resources Minerals, Harum Energy

-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a
-- 
2011-05-30T09:24:42Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-30/indonesia-stock-movers-bumi-resources-minerals-harum-energy.html
Shares of the following companies had
unusual moves in Indonesian trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are as of the 4 p.m. Jakarta-time close.  The  Jakarta Composite index (JCI)  declined 6.24 points, or 0.2
percent, to 3,826.14, the first drop in three days.  PT Bumi Resources Minerals (BRMS IJ), the metal-mining unit
of  Indonesia ’s biggest coal producer, PT Bumi Resources, fell
1.4 percent to 690 rupiah, the most in a week. Bumi Resource
Minerals’ first-quarter net income declined to 138.5 billion
rupiah ($16.2 million) from 271.3 billion rupiah a year earlier
as gold and copper production at its affiliate PT Newmont Nusa
Tenggara dropped, it said.  PT Buana Listya Tama (BULL IJ), a shipping company, gained
2.4 percent to 172 rupiah, advancing for a fourth day. Buana
Listya’s first-quarter net income rose to 85.17 billion rupiah
from 38.94 billion rupiah a year earlier, it said in a statement
published in Investor Daily today.  PT Harum Energy (HRUM IJ), an Indonesian coal producer,
lost 2.6 percent to 9,300 rupiah, the steepest decline since May
6. PT Karunia Bara Perkasa is seeking to raise up to $301
million from sale of shares in the company, according to a term
sheet sent to investors. Karunia Bara is offering 270 million
Harum Energy shares at 9,050 rupiah to 9,550 rupiah each, the
terms show.  PT Nusantara Infrastructure (META IJ), a construction
services provider, rose 2.1 percent to 245 rupiah, gaining for a
third straight day, the longest winning streak since the three
days ended Jan. 14. Nusantara has joined a tender for a water
project in East Java province valued at 1.8 trillion rupiah, PT
Recapital Securities said in a note today. Nusantara President
Director Muhammad Ramdani Basri couldn’t be reached when called
at his office.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Berni Moestafa in Jakarta at 
